body:
I'm not sure this is an issue, it might just be unintuitive or undocumented.

Consider the following code:

``` rust
enum Color {
    Black,
    White
}

impl Color {
    fn new(input: &str) -> Result<Color, &str> {
        match input {
            "black" => Ok(Color::Black),
            "white" => Ok(Color::White),
            _ => Err("invalid color")
        }
    }
}
```

It works nicely; however, when I applied a method to the input value that turned it to a `String` and prefixed it with a `&` expecting it to behave like `&str`, the `match` no longer works and the following code:

``` rust
impl Color {
    fn new(input: &str) -> Result<Color, &str> {
        match &input.to_lowercase() {
            "black" => Ok(Color::Black),
            "white" => Ok(Color::White),
            _ => Err("invalid color")
        }
    }
}
```

returns the following error:

``` rust
test.rs:17:13: 17:20 error: mismatched types [E0308]
test.rs:17             "black" => Ok(Color::Black),
                       ^~~~~~~
test.rs:17:13: 17:20 help: run `rustc --explain E0308` to see a detailed explanation
test.rs:17:13: 17:20 note: expected type `&std::string::String`
test.rs:17:13: 17:20 note:    found type `&'static str`
```

Is this expected? I know there are easy workarounds as applying `as_ref()` or `as_str()`, but I think this behavior is at least unintuitive.
